      "h": "Why Demographic Gaps Persist in Texican Studies",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Historical demographic data on Texicans is incomplete due to inconsistent record-keeping and overlapping identities with other settlers. This limits precise understanding of their population dynamics and social organization.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from Class setup, learner profile, and research rules; jinxschwartz.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Sparse census and population records from early Texas frontier</li><li>Difficulty distinguishing Texicans from other groups in records</li><li>Limited data on family structures and community sizes</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>For instance, census records often grouped Texicans with Anglo settlers or Mexicans, obscuring distinct Texican population counts.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Review a sample census excerpt and identify challenges in isolating Texican individuals.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all early Texas settlers labeled as 'Texans' were Texicans without verifying cultural or ethnic background.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> Class setup, learner profile, and research rules; jinxschwartz.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s1\">[1]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup></p>"
